    q: "My Whirlpool top-load washer is stuck on the sensing cycle. What causes that?",
    a: "The most common cause is a failed shift actuator — a component on Whirlpool's direct drive top-load platform that physically shifts the tub between agitation mode and spin mode. When the actuator fails, the control board can't confirm the tub position and the washer stalls on sensing indefinitely. Before replacing the actuator, we also check the lid lock assembly and the water inlet valve. The shift actuator is a $40-50 part and is the correct diagnosis in the majority of sensing-stuck calls we handle."
